reviewDescription: I *LOVE* these prenatal vitamins!  The flavors are excellent- they come in strawberry-banana, orange, and lemon.  And the gummy texture is perfect- not too chewy, not too tough. reviewDescription: Unfortunately I have to give these vitamins by Mama Bear only 4 stars, after input from my 3 year old.My personal opinion is a 5 star review.  They taste great, are affordable, and have a very short and natural ingredient list.My 3 old, strangely enough, refuses to eat them.  She actually spit them out, which I honestly couldn't believe.  She has had both the Paw Patrol gummie vitamins that you can get at Wal-Mart and the Zarbee's gummie vitamins off of Amazon, and likes both of these (prefers the Paw Patrol of course).The Mama Bear Organic Kids Multivitamin gummies are shaped similar to the Dots candy, and at first they feel like they're going to be a hard texture (and possibly a choking hazard) but after you bite into them, they're suprisingly soft and very similar to the texture of a Swedish Fish candy.  And they literally taste just like candy.  If I REALLY concentrate, I can detect a very subtle "vitamin" taste, and maybe my daughter's taste buds are way more sensitive than mine, but I think these things are absolutely delicious!!The serving for my daughter's age is 2 gummies per day, whereas her other vitamins she only gets one gummie.  Her loss I guess - it looks like the Mama Bear vitamins are mine.  Or maybe I'll be nice and save them to see if she acquires a taste for them in a couple of months (if I can resist eating them all!).I'm disappointed my daughter doesn't like these.  I think they're a good choice of vitamin for our little ones and would absolutely buy them in the future if she decides to try them again and likes them.Two thumbs up from this mama, and two thumbs down from my 3 year old.  Keep in mind, she also doesn't like mashed potatoes....so that goes to show you how poor her taste in flavors is. :)

reviewDescription: This vegan kid’s multivitamin by Mama Bear (an Amazon Brand) tastes good like fruit flavored candy and is easy to chew. It’s nonGMO, organic and appears to have reasonable daily values and lacks a bunch of filler.  This vitamin isn’t derived from whole foods and is instead synthetically derived like most vitamins. It doesn’t have filler or junk like artificial dyes, and it uses fruit pectin instead of gelatin (usually derived from pork skin). I prefer pectin to gelatin myself.This multi contains Vitamin D2 from ergocalciferol (an irradiated plant derived material) instead of Vitamin D3 as cholecalciferol (derived from lanolin in sheep’s wool).  Experts like Dr. Weil recommend that even vegans take D3 as cholecalciferol as it’s more effective than D2. My son isn’t vegan, so I wouldn’t choose this multi that lacks D3 for him. But for those with a diet incompatible with taking D3, this seems like a good kid’s multivitamin. 4 stars.
reviewTitle: Good Kid’s Multivitamin For Vegans Who Can’t Take Vitamin D3- This Has Less Effective Vitamin D2

reviewDescription: These Mama Bear Organic Kids Multivitamins are rounded gumdrop shaped vitamins that are easy (and enjoyable) for both kids and adults to supplement their diets with. The texture is less gummy and more Swedish Fish candies, with a dense feeling chew that doesn't chew back like regular gummy bears do. reviewDescription: This is listed as comparable to smarty pants. If you actually compared both products smarty pants contains the natural l-methylfolate form of folate and this product contains man made version folic acid. reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on January 10, 2019

reviewDescription: I am trying to live a more organic, natural lifestyle. Anyone else trying to do that knows how difficult and exhausting it is to educate yourself on ingredients and have to thoroughly vet everything you buy. Sometimes we mess up, but luckily I caught this in time and canceled the order. I purchased these since they were non gmo, organic, not covered in sugar,  and much less expensive than my normal organic (whole food) gummy. Now I realize why.These have synthetic folate (folic acid) and who knows what else fake as it's very hard to research vitamins (many sites just say something is 'a form' of a vitamins without telling you it's a natural form or not) and the folic acid is all I need to know. I did look up "zinc citrate' -as I've never seen zinc labeled that way- and NIHM just called it "an alternate compound". Not very comforting.This is another case where I really don't understand why this product has a USDA organic label?  But it goes to show that you can't just blindy trust it; it's a good step but so much more needs to be done. Also this confirms you really do get what you pay for when it comes to natural and organic products; I'll stick to my more expensive 100% whole food gummy.
reviewedIn: Reviewed in the United States on April 9, 2020

reviewDescription: This product is full of synthetic vitamin ingredients.  Not only does the human body not process or use synthetics the same way as whole natural versions, but some people can't even absorb them due to the MTHFR gene. Vitamins extracted from whole foods are the only way to go. supplements can be dangerous and this one clearly poses risk.
